
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Labor Market Mobility and Cash Compensation: The Moderating Effects of Race and Gender
AU  - Dreher, George F.
AU  - Cox, Taylor H.
Y1  - 2000/10/01
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/1556417
DO  - 10.5465/1556417
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 890
EP  - 900
VL  - 43
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Building upon the gender-based study conducted by Brett and Stroh (1997), we examined the moderating effects of gender and race on the relationship between changing employers and compensation attainment. The results suggest that, among graduates of M.B.A. (master of business administration) programs, the pay premium associated with an external labor market strategy is primarily a white-male phenomenon. White-male pay differentials were observed only among graduates who changed employers. These results challenge traditional labor-economic models of the compensation attainment process.
AB  - Building upon the gender-based study conducted by Brett and Stroh (1997), we examined the moderating effects of gender and race on the relationship between changing employers and compensation attainment. The results suggest that, among graduates of M.B.A. (master of business administration) programs, the pay premium associated with an external labor market strategy is primarily a white-male phenomenon. White-male pay differentials were observed only among graduates who changed employers. These results challenge traditional labor-economic models of the compensation attainment process.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/1556417
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/1556417
Y2  - 2026/04/24
