TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Paradox of Success: An Archival and a Laboratory Study of Strategic Persistence Following Radical Environmental Change
AU  - Audia, Pino G.
AU  - Locke, Edwin A.
AU  - Smith, Ken G.
Y1  - 2000/10/01
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/1556413
DO  - 10.5465/1556413
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 837
EP  - 853
VL  - 43
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - An archival study of the airline and trucking industries over a ten-year period and a laboratory study revealed that greater past success led to greater strategic persistence after a radical environmental change, and such persistence induced performance declines. The laboratory study also demonstrated that dysfunctional persistence is due to greater satisfaction with past performance, more confidence in the correctness of current strategies, higher goals and self-efficacy, and less seeking of information from critics.
AB  - An archival study of the airline and trucking industries over a ten-year period and a laboratory study revealed that greater past success led to greater strategic persistence after a radical environmental change, and such persistence induced performance declines. The laboratory study also demonstrated that dysfunctional persistence is due to greater satisfaction with past performance, more confidence in the correctness of current strategies, higher goals and self-efficacy, and less seeking of information from critics.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/1556413
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/1556413
