TY  - JOUR
T1  - Marketing Niche Entry Decisions: Competition, Learning, and Strategy in Tokyo Banking, 1894–1936
AU  - Greve, Henrich R.
Y1  - 2000/10/01
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/1556412
DO  - 10.5465/1556412
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 816
EP  - 836
VL  - 43
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - An organization's choice of a branch location can be analyzed as a market niche entry decision. This study builds theory on how an organization's decision makers evaluate market niches on the basis of competitive environment, learning from others, the organization's own experience, and proactive strategy, and it tests the theory with data on branch entry decisions of early Tokyo banks. Analysis of how decisions were affected by density dependence, mimetic isomorphism, decision-making momentum, and mutual forbearance shows strong evidence of influence from the local competitive environment, the actions of large organizations, and the organization's experience, and weaker evidence of proactive strategy.
AB  - An organization's choice of a branch location can be analyzed as a market niche entry decision. This study builds theory on how an organization's decision makers evaluate market niches on the basis of competitive environment, learning from others, the organization's own experience, and proactive strategy, and it tests the theory with data on branch entry decisions of early Tokyo banks. Analysis of how decisions were affected by density dependence, mimetic isomorphism, decision-making momentum, and mutual forbearance shows strong evidence of influence from the local competitive environment, the actions of large organizations, and the organization's experience, and weaker evidence of proactive strategy.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/1556412
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/1556412
Y2  - 2026/04/24
